1
00:01:12,732 --> 00:01:14,860
The Ching Dynasty
during the late 19th century,

2
00:01:15,101 --> 00:01:16,967
was a declining empire

3
00:01:17,170 --> 00:01:18,569
besieged with domestic
and foreign problems.

4
00:01:19,072 --> 00:01:22,633
While the Ching Empire
had yet to recover

5
00:01:23,143 --> 00:01:26,670
from the Taiping Rebellion in 1851,

6
00:01:30,517 --> 00:01:33,111
the British-French Alliance in 1858

7
00:01:33,353 --> 00:01:34,980
forced the Ching Empire to open

8
00:01:35,155 --> 00:01:38,489
Anping, Tamsui, Chilung,
and Takou ports

9
00:01:38,725 --> 00:01:41,717
to foreign trade.

10
00:01:42,929 --> 00:01:44,556
As the ports opened,

11
00:01:44,798 --> 00:01:49,235
western merchants,
adventurers and missionaries

12
00:01:49,569 --> 00:01:51,435
all came to Taiwan.

13
00:01:53,373 --> 00:01:55,034
After having been isolated
for over a century,

14
00:01:55,275 --> 00:01:57,300
Taiwan and the western world

15
00:01:57,544 --> 00:01:59,205
once again met.

16
00:02:00,647 --> 00:02:03,173
However, this time,

17
00:02:03,416 --> 00:02:05,350
Western countries
not only came to trade,

18
00:02:05,585 --> 00:02:08,850
but also brought
new cultural impact.

19
00:02:09,656 --> 00:02:11,146
After the ports were opened,

20
00:02:11,391 --> 00:02:13,655
western merchants
came to Taiwan

21
00:02:13,893 --> 00:02:15,452
to seek business opportunities.

22
00:02:16,996 --> 00:02:18,054
Tataocheng in Taipei

23
00:02:18,298 --> 00:02:21,290
became a trading center for
Taiwan tea leaves,

24
00:02:21,534 --> 00:02:24,970
with exports reaching
its peak in 1893.

25
00:02:25,238 --> 00:02:26,467
Every tea season,
the average number of workers

26
00:02:26,706 --> 00:02:29,641
in and out of Tataocheng ...

27
00:02:29,876 --> 00:02:32,004
each day was over 20,000

28
00:02:32,879 --> 00:02:35,348
while another 10,000 workers

29
00:02:35,582 --> 00:02:38,745
shuttled between Tataocheng
and Fuchien.

30
00:02:43,323 --> 00:02:45,815
Having lived in Taiwan
for 32 years,

31
00:02:46,059 --> 00:02:47,584
British merchant John Dodd

32
00:02:47,827 --> 00:02:48,692
could be regarded as the
greatest contributor

33
00:02:48,928 --> 00:02:52,193
to the modernization
of Wulong tea in Taiwan.

34
00:02:52,432 --> 00:02:54,161
During his stay in Taiwan,

35
00:02:54,401 --> 00:02:56,768
Dodd witnessed the
flourishing of Tamsui Harbor

36
00:02:57,036 --> 00:02:59,095
and the prosperity of Tataocheng.

37
00:02:59,539 --> 00:03:01,405
In his diary, Dodd recorded

38
00:03:01,641 --> 00:03:05,635
the busy activities there
during tea season.

39
00:03:09,549 --> 00:03:12,541
Tataocheng was abound with
these “leaves of happiness,”

40
00:03:12,786 --> 00:03:15,983
because they brought big profits.

41
00:03:16,623 --> 00:03:18,557
Female tea pickers there were
all dressed up beautifully.

42
00:03:18,792 --> 00:03:22,729
They put magnolias on their

43
00:03:23,163 --> 00:03:28,499
hair and gold and silver rings
on their fingers.

44
00:03:28,735 --> 00:03:31,602
They chatted as they picked
tea leaves.

45
00:03:32,005 --> 00:03:33,268
Droves of female tea pickers

46
00:03:33,506 --> 00:03:37,568
filled the city with
joyous atmosphere.

47
00:03:40,280 --> 00:03:42,977
In 1867, Dodd established

48
00:03:43,183 --> 00:03:45,277
a tea factory in Bangka.

49
00:03:45,652 --> 00:03:48,417
In 1868, he imported Wulong

50
00:03:48,655 --> 00:03:50,521
from Anhsi in Fuchien,

51
00:03:50,790 --> 00:03:53,851
and tried to sell Wulong tea
in Macao the following year.

52
00:03:54,093 --> 00:03:55,492
In 1869,

53
00:03:55,728 --> 00:03:59,289
he established Dodd & Co.
In Tataocheng.

54
00:04:01,901 --> 00:04:04,393
In the same year, he used two junks

55
00:04:04,637 --> 00:04:07,299
to ship 23,000 pounds of
Wulong tea

56
00:04:07,540 --> 00:04:08,632
to New York for sale.

57
00:04:08,875 --> 00:04:10,604
The tea became very popular,

58
00:04:10,877 --> 00:04:14,074
and other companies
quickly followed suit.

59
00:04:14,314 --> 00:04:16,942
As a result, tea commerce
in Taiwan flourished.

60
00:04:22,322 --> 00:04:23,847
Tataocheng in Taipei became

61
00:04:24,090 --> 00:04:26,855
the hub of western companies
and tea merchants.

62
00:04:27,227 --> 00:04:28,626
In 1872,

63
00:04:28,862 --> 00:04:31,490
from Hsiahai Chenghuang Temple,
Tihua Street,

64
00:04:31,731 --> 00:04:33,699
up to the banks of Tamsui River,

65
00:04:33,933 --> 00:04:35,765
there were six foreign companies

66
00:04:36,002 --> 00:04:39,063
and over 150 tea factories.

67
00:04:39,339 --> 00:04:42,536
As tea leaves became
Taiwan's major export,

68
00:04:42,775 --> 00:04:45,210
Tataocheng flourished to become

69
00:04:45,445 --> 00:04:48,540
a place filled with the aroma
of tea and tea flowers.

70
00:05:16,309 --> 00:05:18,004
After the ports were opened
for trade,

71
00:05:18,177 --> 00:05:21,044
the Ching Empire started to
allow missionaries

72
00:05:21,281 --> 00:05:23,511
from the West to spread religion
at the ports.

73
00:05:24,050 --> 00:05:26,382
Since most of the missionaries

74
00:05:26,619 --> 00:05:29,384
had medical training,

75
00:05:29,789 --> 00:05:31,223
the female missionaries

76
00:05:31,457 --> 00:05:34,119
also worked as nurses.

77
00:05:34,394 --> 00:05:36,021
It can be said that
the development of churches in Taiwan

78
00:05:36,262 --> 00:05:37,457
was founded on

79
00:05:37,697 --> 00:05:40,166
medical and missionary work

80
00:06:02,188 --> 00:06:04,714
In 1865, Dr. James L. Maxwell

81
00:06:05,024 --> 00:06:07,857
arrived in Tainan
for medical missionary work

82
00:06:08,094 --> 00:06:10,426
and established
the first Presbyterian Church

83
00:06:10,663 --> 00:06:13,257
in southern Taiwan.

84
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:16,601
Dr. Maxwell used quinine
and surgery

85
00:06:16,836 --> 00:06:20,568
to treat patients with
cataract and bladder stone.

86
00:06:20,807 --> 00:06:24,004
Because his work threatened
local Han Chinese physicians,

87
00:06:24,644 --> 00:06:26,510
they spread rumors

88
00:06:26,746 --> 00:06:29,443
that Dr. Maxwell used
human brain to make opium.

89
00:06:29,682 --> 00:06:31,411
The rumor caused a public uproar.

90
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:48,198
A large mob

91
00:06:48,434 --> 00:06:51,028
surrounded his residence
in Kanhsi Street

92
00:06:51,204 --> 00:06:53,832
and destroyed the church and clinic.

93
00:06:54,340 --> 00:06:56,206
To prevent escalation of the uproar,

94
00:06:56,442 --> 00:06:58,843
city officials ordered Doctor Maxwell
to leave the city.

95
00:06:59,078 --> 00:07:02,139
Less than 24 days after
starting his missionary work,

96
00:07:02,382 --> 00:07:03,178
Dr. Maxwell was forced

97
00:07:03,416 --> 00:07:05,817
to move to a place protected
by the British consulate,

98
00:07:06,052 --> 00:07:08,544
which was present-day
Chichin in Kaohsiung,

99
00:07:08,788 --> 00:07:11,985
where he continued
his medical and missionary work.

100
00:07:15,862 --> 00:07:17,660
In 1870,

101
00:07:17,897 --> 00:07:19,991
Dr. Maxwell's missionary effort

102
00:07:20,233 --> 00:07:22,031
started to bear fruit.

103
00:07:22,368 --> 00:07:23,301
Some of his patients

104
00:07:23,536 --> 00:07:26,995
started to praise his good work,

105
00:07:30,276 --> 00:07:32,370
and more patients came to see him.

106
00:07:32,612 --> 00:07:35,104
They brought the Gospel
they heard in the clinic

107
00:07:35,348 --> 00:07:37,316
back to their villages.

108
00:07:37,550 --> 00:07:38,312
This was the beginning of

109
00:07:38,551 --> 00:07:41,384
the spread of churches
in southern Taiwan.

110
00:07:48,795 --> 00:07:51,264
On March 9, 1872,

111
00:07:52,732 --> 00:07:54,166
the Sea Dragon,
which was traveling

112
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:57,563
in the Taiwan Strait,
sailed into Tamsui Harbor.

113
00:07:58,438 --> 00:08:00,805
A Canadian youth
traveling onboard

114
00:08:01,074 --> 00:08:03,600
fell in love with Tamsui and

115
00:08:03,876 --> 00:08:06,971
decided to dedicate his life
to this land.

116
00:08:07,180 --> 00:08:09,808
His subsequent medical,
educational,

117
00:08:10,049 --> 00:08:11,346
and missionary work in Taiwan

118
00:08:11,584 --> 00:08:13,177
had significant influence
on Taiwan's culture

119
00:08:13,419 --> 00:08:16,184
This young man was
Dr. George Mackay.

120
00:08:16,723 --> 00:08:19,021
There seems to be an invisible line

121
00:08:19,258 --> 00:08:21,727
that draws me
to this beautiful island.

122
00:08:25,098 --> 00:08:27,294
Dr. Mackay wrote in his diary.

123
00:08:27,533 --> 00:08:30,002
Dr. Mackay had been sent by
Canada's Presbyterian Church

124
00:08:30,169 --> 00:08:32,001
to do missionary work in Taiwan.

125
00:08:32,205 --> 00:08:35,903
When I arrived at the estuary
of Tamsui River

126
00:08:36,642 --> 00:08:38,610
in northern Taiwan,
I looked to the north and south,

127
00:08:38,845 --> 00:08:41,871
then gazed at the
green mountains inland.

128
00:08:42,115 --> 00:08:44,550
I felt spiritually satisfied

129
00:08:44,784 --> 00:08:46,878
and peaceful.

130
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:49,248
A clear voice was telling me:

131
00:08:49,489 --> 00:08:51,321
This is the place

132
00:08:53,059 --> 00:08:55,289
Dr. Mackay used Tamsui as
his base for missionary work

133
00:08:55,528 --> 00:08:57,462
in northern Taiwan and
provided medical services

134
00:08:57,697 --> 00:09:01,463
to supplement his missionary work.

135
00:09:16,883 --> 00:09:17,975
Dr. Mackay understood that

136
00:09:18,184 --> 00:09:20,812
he must first learn to speak
fluent Taiwanese to be able

137
00:09:21,053 --> 00:09:24,284
to establish a foundation
for spreading the Gospel.

138
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:42,701
On Jan. 25.

139
00:09:42,942 --> 00:09:46,901
I learned 100 words
and chanted the Chinese aloud.

140
00:09:46,979 --> 00:09:49,243
Reading in a loud way
is a very good way

141
00:09:49,315 --> 00:09:51,215
to learn a new language.

142
00:09:54,854 --> 00:09:56,219
March 4th

143
00:09:56,455 --> 00:09:59,755
I exerted myself to read
Chinese books diligently,

144
00:10:00,059 --> 00:10:02,391
and reviewed all that
I've learned before.

145
00:10:02,628 --> 00:10:05,563
At the same time,
I added 100 new words.

146
00:10:06,098 --> 00:10:09,898
Currently, I know 240 characters by heart.

147
00:10:20,780 --> 00:10:22,646
Dr. Mackay traveled
throughout Taiwan

148
00:10:22,882 --> 00:10:25,249
living together with the locals

149
00:10:29,322 --> 00:10:32,724
in Wuku, Taoyuan, Chungli,
and Hsinkang.

150
00:10:33,025 --> 00:10:36,325
He visited aborigines in Neishe
for missionary work.

151
00:10:39,565 --> 00:10:42,227
Many people opposed Christianity.

152
00:10:42,468 --> 00:10:44,732
Because they don't have
medicine for their sickness,

153
00:10:45,037 --> 00:10:47,005
they came to me, a foreigner.

154
00:10:47,240 --> 00:10:51,802
From being enemies
we became friends.

155
00:10:52,245 --> 00:10:55,215
The Han Chinese were resilient.

156
00:10:55,448 --> 00:10:58,008
They can endure the pain
from surgery.

157
00:10:58,184 --> 00:11:00,312
It's really amazing

158
00:11:00,553 --> 00:11:02,385
Since 1873,

159
00:11:02,622 --> 00:11:05,182
in 30 years of medical service
in Taiwan,

160
00:11:05,424 --> 00:11:08,291
Dr. Mackay extracted
at least 21,000 teeth.

161
00:11:09,395 --> 00:11:12,228
On March 18, 1873,

162
00:11:13,065 --> 00:11:15,659
a visitor arrived at
the Tamsui church to visit

163
00:11:15,902 --> 00:11:19,236
Rev. Mackay, who had succeed
in his missionary work.

164
00:11:25,011 --> 00:11:27,173
The visitor was
Rev. William Campbell,

165
00:11:27,413 --> 00:11:28,778
who was sent by the
English Presbyterian Church

166
00:11:29,015 --> 00:11:32,610
to do missionary work in Taiwan.

167
00:11:32,852 --> 00:11:34,149
These two missionaries

168
00:11:34,387 --> 00:11:36,617
became the two underpinnings

169
00:11:36,856 --> 00:11:39,154
of the Presbyterian Church,

170
00:11:39,392 --> 00:11:41,190
which spread Christianity in
southern and northern Taiwan

171
00:11:43,529 --> 00:11:45,088
Dr. Mackay was a diligent traveler.

172
00:11:45,331 --> 00:11:46,662
He traveled to Hsuehshan,

173
00:11:46,899 --> 00:11:49,834
the plains of Lanyang,
the east coast in Hualien

174
00:11:50,069 --> 00:11:51,628
and the three islets in the north.

175
00:11:51,871 --> 00:11:53,396
Despite the many dangers
and difficulties,

176
00:11:53,639 --> 00:11:56,438
Dr. Mackay remained determined
to do missionary work.

177
00:12:48,527 --> 00:12:51,986
Rev. Campbell and I went
together to Wukukeng,

178
00:12:52,164 --> 00:12:55,259
Chouli, Bangka, Chungli,

179
00:12:55,501 --> 00:12:58,994
Chuchian, Hsinkang, and Neishe.

180
00:12:59,238 --> 00:13:02,674
From Neishe, Rev. Campbell
proceeded north,

181
00:13:02,942 --> 00:13:05,536
while I ventured deep
into the mountains.

182
00:13:05,978 --> 00:13:09,175
Mountain trails were rugged
and the grasses were tall.

183
00:13:09,415 --> 00:13:12,282
After much difficulty,
we arrived at a summit,

184
00:13:12,685 --> 00:13:14,847
and shouted.

185
00:13:16,689 --> 00:13:20,455
Soon, I heard gun shots from
the base of the mountain.

186
00:13:24,530 --> 00:13:27,795
Another team of raw
barbarians were waiting.

187
00:13:32,371 --> 00:13:35,238
I've spent 8 pleasant days
with Mr. Mackay

188
00:13:35,474 --> 00:13:38,102
and now I see much hope for the future.

189
00:13:38,344 --> 00:13:41,780
I now realized that I should return
to the original missionary

190
00:13:41,847 --> 00:13:44,976
in Changhua to make a fresh start.

191
00:13:51,223 --> 00:13:52,452
Walking in the big cities,

192
00:13:52,691 --> 00:13:54,523
we often meet blind people.

193
00:13:54,760 --> 00:13:56,057
Many Chinese suffered from

194
00:13:56,128 --> 00:13:58,392
small pox and poor hygiene.

195
00:13:58,631 --> 00:14:01,157
So we are not really surprised.

196
00:14:03,335 --> 00:14:05,133
Most blind people are beggars

197
00:14:05,371 --> 00:14:07,135
or worked as fortunetellers.

198
00:14:07,373 --> 00:14:12,174
Some worked as threshers or
step tread mill to make their living.

199
00:14:22,588 --> 00:14:25,819
As the missionary work expanded,

200
00:14:26,058 --> 00:14:29,494
Dr. Mackay established the

201
00:14:29,728 --> 00:14:31,526
Oxford College in 1883

202
00:14:32,531 --> 00:14:34,590
and introduced western-type
education.

203
00:14:34,834 --> 00:14:36,598
Dr. Mackay later established

204
00:14:36,836 --> 00:14:38,668
the all-girl Tamsui Girls' School.

205
00:14:45,845 --> 00:14:47,040
In 1885, Rev. Campbell,

206
00:14:47,279 --> 00:14:49,873
who was doing missionary work
in the Tainan area,

207
00:14:50,116 --> 00:14:51,481
established the first school

208
00:14:51,717 --> 00:14:53,811
for the blind in Taiwan.

209
00:14:55,521 --> 00:14:57,114
The school used Roman-script

210
00:14:57,356 --> 00:14:58,846
Braille printing

211
00:14:59,091 --> 00:15:00,752
to publish five books for the blind.

212
00:15:00,993 --> 00:15:04,554
The Braille Gospel and
missionary booklets were

213
00:15:04,797 --> 00:15:07,767
the first Braille books for
the blind in Taiwan, and were

214
00:15:08,033 --> 00:15:10,866
the precursor of education
for the blind in Taiwan.

215
00:15:11,837 --> 00:15:13,032
In 1913, Rev. Campbell
published the New Dictionary

216
00:15:13,272 --> 00:15:16,333
of the Vernacular
or Spoken Language of Amoy

217
00:15:16,575 --> 00:15:20,068
which is still widely in use today.

218
00:15:39,565 --> 00:15:41,659
In 1861, British Vice Consul

219
00:15:41,901 --> 00:15:44,427
Robert Swinhoe became

220
00:15:44,670 --> 00:15:47,503
the first foreign consular
representative to Taiwan.

221
00:15:47,740 --> 00:15:50,038
He was also a typical
English naturalist

222
00:15:50,276 --> 00:15:53,337
of the Victorian Age.

223
00:15:59,652 --> 00:16:02,747
From the perspective of
modern taxonomy,

224
00:16:02,988 --> 00:16:04,478
Swinhoe was the first

225
00:16:04,723 --> 00:16:07,715
to systematically perform

226
00:16:08,027 --> 00:16:09,756
on-site studies, document,
collect samples,

227
00:16:10,029 --> 00:16:11,997
and publish in writing
Taiwan's fauna and flora.

228
00:16:15,134 --> 00:16:16,727
In April 1862,

229
00:16:17,036 --> 00:16:19,733
Swinhoe traveled along
upstream Tahan River and

230
00:16:20,039 --> 00:16:21,529
arrive at Kueihui commune,

231
00:16:21,774 --> 00:16:24,402
which is present-day
Fuhsing Village in Taoyuan,

232
00:16:24,643 --> 00:16:27,374
to investigate the site
and collect samples.

233
00:16:33,752 --> 00:16:35,516
In July of the same year,

234
00:16:35,754 --> 00:16:36,744
he published his pioneering research
into the history

235
00:16:37,056 --> 00:16:39,150
of Taiwan's mammals:

236
00:16:39,391 --> 00:16:41,553
On the Mammals of
the Island of Formosa.

237
00:16:41,794 --> 00:16:42,852
Of the 62 known
mammalian species

238
00:16:43,095 --> 00:16:45,928
in Taiwan today,

239
00:16:46,165 --> 00:16:48,133
Swinhoe recorded 27,

240
00:16:48,367 --> 00:16:50,495
11 of which were new species

241
00:16:50,736 --> 00:16:53,398
that he studied and named.

242
00:16:57,409 --> 00:17:00,777
At around 1863,
Swinhoe published the

243
00:17:01,080 --> 00:17:03,048
The Ornithology of Formosa.

244
00:17:03,282 --> 00:17:04,681
Among the 458 known species

245
00:17:04,917 --> 00:17:07,215
of birds in Taiwan today,

246
00:17:07,453 --> 00:17:09,285
Swinhoe discovered a total of

247
00:17:09,521 --> 00:17:11,546
226 species.

248
00:17:11,857 --> 00:17:13,757
The Swinhoe's Blue Pheasant

249
00:17:14,026 --> 00:17:15,790
found in the mountain areas
of inner Tamsui

250
00:17:16,028 --> 00:17:18,326
was named after him.

251
00:17:18,564 --> 00:17:21,590
Swinhoe's discoveries secured
his place in ornithology.

252
00:17:24,136 --> 00:17:26,400
Another British, Charles Darwin,

253
00:17:26,639 --> 00:17:28,835
had earlier published

254
00:17:29,074 --> 00:17:30,564
The Origin of Species.

255
00:17:31,043 --> 00:17:33,102
It is during this time when
the flora and fauna in Taiwan

256
00:17:33,345 --> 00:17:35,712
gradually became known
to the West.

257
00:17:35,948 --> 00:17:38,246
Taiwan's natural history
and ethnographies also became

258
00:17:38,484 --> 00:17:41,351
important world assets.

259
00:17:43,589 --> 00:17:45,250
In February 1866,

260
00:17:45,491 --> 00:17:48,483
Swinhoe traveled upstream
along Kaoping River

261
00:17:48,727 --> 00:17:51,719
and arrived near present-day
Liukuei and Hsuehshan

262
00:17:51,964 --> 00:17:54,194
to study its biology.

263
00:18:04,076 --> 00:18:06,204
This would be his last
extended field study

264
00:18:06,445 --> 00:18:09,847
during his stay in Taiwan.

265
00:18:17,022 --> 00:18:19,150
In his later published writings,

266
00:18:19,391 --> 00:18:21,985
he described with precision the
broad-leaf forests in the low-altitude

267
00:18:22,227 --> 00:18:25,629
mountain areas in southern Taiwan
over 100 years ago

268
00:18:25,898 --> 00:18:28,595
Swinhoe also eulogized the
beautiful island of Taiwan,

269
00:18:28,834 --> 00:18:31,496
praising its nature and ecology

270
00:18:37,576 --> 00:18:39,135
In the offshore Takou,

271
00:18:39,378 --> 00:18:42,541
there were butterfly paths
like rivers.

272
00:18:44,483 --> 00:18:47,919
And numberable wobblers
in the forest.

273
00:18:48,587 --> 00:18:52,649
Formosa is really
a natural paradise.

274
00:19:10,809 --> 00:19:13,210
On Nov. 6, 1871

275
00:19:13,445 --> 00:19:15,880
a tribute transport ship from
Miyako Island in Ryukyu

276
00:19:16,115 --> 00:19:17,981
encountered a storm at sea,

277
00:19:18,183 --> 00:19:20,515
drifting to Hengchun Peninsula
in southeast Taiwan.

278
00:19:20,753 --> 00:19:22,118
The ship capsized

279
00:19:22,354 --> 00:19:23,480
near Payao Bay.

280
00:19:23,722 --> 00:19:24,814
Three persons drowned,

281
00:19:25,057 --> 00:19:26,582
while 66 reached the shore.

282
00:19:26,825 --> 00:19:30,125
They lost their way and
ventured into Kaoshihfo

283
00:19:40,773 --> 00:19:43,401
commune of the Paiwan tribe.

284
00:19:43,642 --> 00:19:44,734
Because of miscommunication
due to the language barrier,

285
00:19:45,043 --> 00:19:47,239
54 of this batch of Ryukyu people

286
00:19:47,479 --> 00:19:49,345
were killed by the Paiwan tribe.

287
00:19:49,581 --> 00:19:51,208
Only 12 were able to escape

288
00:19:51,450 --> 00:19:55,318
to seek protection in the
Hakka village of Paolichuang.

289
00:19:56,054 --> 00:19:57,749
The killing of the Ryukyu
shipwreck survivors was an

290
00:19:58,056 --> 00:20:00,184
incident that the
Ching administration

291
00:20:00,426 --> 00:20:03,396
regarded as having happened
outside of their jurisdiction.

292
00:20:03,629 --> 00:20:06,155
The passive attitude
of the Ching administration

293
00:20:06,398 --> 00:20:08,332
gave Japan the opportunity

294
00:20:08,567 --> 00:20:11,264
to announce sovereignty
over Ryukyu. Japan also sent

295
00:20:11,503 --> 00:20:15,201
troops to southern Taiwan
to punish the raw barbarians.

296
00:20:15,808 --> 00:20:18,072
On May 7, 1874,

297
00:20:18,310 --> 00:20:21,041
Japanese soldiers landed in
Langchiao Bay in Hengchun,

298
00:20:21,280 --> 00:20:22,042
which is present-day

299
00:20:22,281 --> 00:20:25,251
Sheliao near Checheng, Hengchun.

300
00:20:29,855 --> 00:20:30,720
On May 18,

301
00:20:31,023 --> 00:20:33,993
a small platoon of Japanese
soldiers arrived at

302
00:20:34,226 --> 00:20:35,819
Shihchung River in Hengchun
to survey the Shihmen area.

303
00:20:36,061 --> 00:20:38,393
They were attacked by
residents of Mutan commune.

304
00:21:18,670 --> 00:21:21,002
On May 22, 1874,

305
00:21:21,240 --> 00:21:23,732
the Battle of Shihmen erupted,

306
00:21:29,147 --> 00:21:30,137
and the Japanese
expeditionary force

307
00:21:30,382 --> 00:21:32,851
showed its enormous
military superiority.

308
00:21:43,095 --> 00:21:45,223
The head of Mutan commune and
his son died in the battle.

309
00:21:45,464 --> 00:21:48,525
The Mutan residents continued
their strong resistance.

310
00:21:56,208 --> 00:21:57,198
As the Battle of Shihmen

311
00:21:57,442 --> 00:21:59,171
raged on,

312
00:21:59,411 --> 00:22:02,005
lieutenant-general
Tsugumichi Saigou

313
00:22:02,214 --> 00:22:05,673
landed in Langchiao Bay with
a large number of soldiers.

314
00:22:20,632 --> 00:22:22,498
Japanese victory
in the Battle of Shihmen

315
00:22:22,734 --> 00:22:24,566
shocked communities in Langchiao.

316
00:22:24,803 --> 00:22:26,237
To protect themselves,

317
00:22:27,506 --> 00:22:28,871
on May 25,

318
00:22:29,107 --> 00:22:31,474
members of the Alliance of
the 16 Langchiao Communes,

319
00:22:31,710 --> 00:22:33,872
the head of Soavari commune Isa,

320
00:22:34,112 --> 00:22:37,412
and the head of Chushu commune
Young Tauketok,

321
00:22:37,649 --> 00:22:38,980
under direction of the Japanese,

322
00:22:39,151 --> 00:22:41,518
led the other tribal leaders

323
00:22:41,753 --> 00:22:43,983
to meet with

324
00:22:44,189 --> 00:22:46,157
Saigou for a second time.

325
00:22:47,726 --> 00:22:50,855
At that time, the aborigines
in the Langchiao area,

326
00:22:51,096 --> 00:22:53,997
in southern Taiwan,
which is present-day

327
00:22:54,232 --> 00:22:56,997
Hengchun Peninsula,
lived as 18 separate tribal

328
00:22:57,169 --> 00:22:58,898
communities scattered
all over the region.

329
00:23:01,039 --> 00:23:03,007
Although Isa and Young Tauketok

330
00:23:03,175 --> 00:23:04,734
were elected as

331
00:23:04,977 --> 00:23:07,469
leaders of the Langchiao
18 communes,

332
00:23:08,180 --> 00:23:09,409
in reality,

333
00:23:09,648 --> 00:23:10,979
they did not have power

334
00:23:11,216 --> 00:23:13,617
to restrain the other tribes.

335
00:23:14,152 --> 00:23:16,086
The purpose of the Japanese
in the talk

336
00:23:16,321 --> 00:23:17,311
was to unite the members

337
00:23:17,556 --> 00:23:19,957
of the Langchiao commune alliance

338
00:23:20,158 --> 00:23:22,217
and include the prime culprit of
the Ryukyu killing incident,

339
00:23:22,461 --> 00:23:25,761
which was the intrepid
Mutan commune,

340
00:23:25,998 --> 00:23:27,727
the most powerful among the
Kaoshihfo and 18 communes,

341
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:30,367
as target of military attacks.

342
00:23:36,642 --> 00:23:39,703
Members of the
Langchiao commune alliance

343
00:23:40,012 --> 00:23:44,745
should not protect the Mutan people,

344
00:23:45,017 --> 00:23:47,645
and should help the Japanese
soldiers capture Mutan

345
00:23:47,886 --> 00:23:53,188
warriors who had escaped
into their commune to

346
00:23:53,425 --> 00:23:58,522
show loyalty to the alliance
between both parties.

347
00:23:58,764 --> 00:24:08,606
I guarantee the Kueitsaichiao
communes will cease to view

348
00:24:08,840 --> 00:24:15,678
the Japanese as enemies.

349
00:24:15,914 --> 00:24:21,512
Should any tribe attack the
Japanese soldiers in the future,

350
00:24:21,753 --> 00:24:26,486
I will personally lead their
army to suppress the attack.

351
00:24:26,725 --> 00:24:29,854
The alliance members should
abide by the above demands

352
00:24:30,095 --> 00:24:41,200
To prevent killings by mistake,
all you have to do is raise the flag.

353
00:25:41,633 --> 00:25:43,533
On June 1, 1874,

354
00:25:43,769 --> 00:25:47,103
Saigou led 1360 soldiers to

355
00:25:47,339 --> 00:25:49,865
attack Mutan commune from
three directions:

356
00:25:50,108 --> 00:25:52,406
Shihmen, Chushe, and Fengkang.

357
00:25:52,644 --> 00:25:53,543
On June 3,

358
00:25:53,779 --> 00:25:55,577
Japanese soldiers captured
Mutan commune.

359
00:25:55,814 --> 00:25:57,782
Faced with superior
Japanese military strength,

360
00:25:58,083 --> 00:26:00,142
Mutan commune finally surrendered.

361
00:26:00,385 --> 00:26:01,750
The 18 Langchiao communes

362
00:26:01,987 --> 00:26:04,979
submitted themselves under
Japanese occupational force.

363
00:26:11,530 --> 00:26:12,656
After the Meiji Restoration,

364
00:26:12,898 --> 00:26:14,525
the Mutan Incident was

365
00:26:14,766 --> 00:26:17,133
the first time that Japan sent
their soldiers abroad.

366
00:26:21,306 --> 00:26:22,899
Because the incident

367
00:26:23,141 --> 00:26:25,405
attracted the attention of the
British and American media,

368
00:26:25,644 --> 00:26:27,169
British diplomat to
China Thomas Wade

369
00:26:27,412 --> 00:26:30,677
acted as mediator between
the Ching Dynasty and Japan.

370
00:26:30,916 --> 00:26:33,442
A treaty was signed,

371
00:26:33,685 --> 00:26:34,743
which called for the withdrawal
of the Japanese soldiers

372
00:26:35,053 --> 00:26:37,112
and compensation from
the Ching administration.

373
00:26:37,556 --> 00:26:39,615
One year after the Mutan Incident,

374
00:26:39,858 --> 00:26:42,225
on Jan. 12, 1875,

375
00:26:42,460 --> 00:26:44,690
the Ching Emperor Tungchih
passed away,

376
00:26:44,930 --> 00:26:48,491
and the Empress Dowager
officially came into power.

377
00:26:48,733 --> 00:26:51,031
The military invasion resulting
from the Ryukyu shipwreck

378
00:26:51,203 --> 00:26:52,568
finally came to a close

379
00:26:52,804 --> 00:26:54,795
Yet a battle of a larger scale

380
00:26:55,073 --> 00:26:57,542
loomed.

381
00:27:11,022 --> 00:27:13,650
10 years after the Mutan Incident,

382
00:27:13,892 --> 00:27:15,382
Taiwan, for no reason,
was drawn into another

383
00:27:15,627 --> 00:27:17,994
war between imperialist empires.

384
00:27:18,563 --> 00:27:19,894
In Indochina,

385
00:27:20,131 --> 00:27:22,725
the French were plotting
to extend their power into

386
00:27:23,034 --> 00:27:26,004
the Ching vassal state Annan.

387
00:27:26,771 --> 00:27:28,705
To force the hand of
the Ching Empire,

388
00:27:28,940 --> 00:27:32,001
the French decided to attack
China's commercial ports.

389
00:27:32,210 --> 00:27:33,871
As a result, Taiwan became

390
00:27:34,112 --> 00:27:36,308
a battleground in the
Sino-French war.

391
00:27:37,415 --> 00:27:38,211
At that time, Liu Ming-chuan

392
00:27:38,450 --> 00:27:41,818
was dispatched to oversee
military affairs to Taiwan,

393
00:27:43,622 --> 00:27:46,114
where he augmented the defense of

394
00:27:46,358 --> 00:27:48,224
Chilung, Tamsui, and Penghu.

395
00:27:56,067 --> 00:27:58,729
Amedee Courbet, admiral of
the Far East French fleet,

396
00:27:58,970 --> 00:28:02,634
was under orders to capture
Chilung and the coal mines.

397
00:28:19,491 --> 00:28:21,858
On Aug. 26, 1884,

398
00:28:22,093 --> 00:28:24,323
the Ching Empire declared war
against France.

399
00:28:28,400 --> 00:28:29,458
On Oct. 1, 1884,

400
00:28:29,701 --> 00:28:32,033
Courbet led ten battleships

401
00:28:32,270 --> 00:28:33,465
and over 2000 marines
and artillery

402
00:28:33,705 --> 00:28:36,731
reinforcements from Vietnam

403
00:28:37,042 --> 00:28:39,875
and launched a second attack
on Chilung.

404
00:28:40,312 --> 00:28:42,747
Courbet's retinue at the time

405
00:28:43,048 --> 00:28:44,345
was Orderly Jean,

406
00:28:44,582 --> 00:28:46,880
who recorded his experience

407
00:28:47,118 --> 00:28:50,281
in this battle in the Far East.

408
00:28:51,656 --> 00:28:54,387
Our cannons destroyed everything,

409
00:28:54,626 --> 00:28:57,254
but the Ching army quickly
rebuilt their defense line.

410
00:28:57,495 --> 00:29:02,490
It was like a spider
reweaving its web.

411
00:29:02,734 --> 00:29:07,262
There were over 6000 Ching
defenders.

412
00:29:15,046 --> 00:29:16,571
During the Sino-French War,

413
00:29:16,815 --> 00:29:18,180
British tea merchant

414
00:29:18,416 --> 00:29:19,611
John Dodd in his diary

415
00:29:19,851 --> 00:29:22,980
described the French landing
in Hsientung, Chilung,

416
00:29:23,154 --> 00:29:25,987
and Liu's hasty abandon
of the defense.

417
00:29:27,692 --> 00:29:28,818
The catastrophe.

418
00:29:29,060 --> 00:29:32,257
French troops landed in Kelang
on October 1st.

419
00:29:32,497 --> 00:29:36,525
Although they have been compelled twice
by the garrison troops to draw back,

420
00:29:36,601 --> 00:29:39,366
the French troops finally seized
the harbor.

421
00:29:39,604 --> 00:29:42,005
The Ching troops
were gradually pushed back.

422
00:29:42,240 --> 00:29:44,402
There were many casualties
in the battle,

423
00:29:44,476 --> 00:29:46,308
and many taken prisoner.

424
00:29:46,411 --> 00:29:51,144
Liu Ming-chuan finally ordered
a retreat to Tataocheng and Tamsui.

425
00:29:51,383 --> 00:29:52,145
On Oct. 2,

426
00:29:52,384 --> 00:29:55,410
over 1000 French landed and
captured Chilung Harbor,

427
00:29:55,653 --> 00:29:58,714
making it their official stronghold
in Taiwan.

428
00:29:58,957 --> 00:30:00,618
By this time, Liu had

429
00:30:00,859 --> 00:30:02,793
transferred troops
defending Chilung

430
00:30:03,061 --> 00:30:04,790
to Tamsui.

431
00:30:12,070 --> 00:30:14,767
General Sun Kai-hua of the
Hsiang army defending Tamsui

432
00:30:15,006 --> 00:30:17,236
predicted a French attack,
so he loaded boats with rocks and

433
00:30:18,777 --> 00:30:21,769
sunk them
at the Tamsui River estuary.

434
00:30:22,013 --> 00:30:24,038
He also laid water mines
at the harbor to prevent

435
00:30:24,282 --> 00:30:27,718
the French from pushing
deep into the city of Taipei.

436
00:30:42,067 --> 00:30:45,162
At 10 a.m,, Oct. 8, 1884,

437
00:30:45,403 --> 00:30:47,997
Courbet sent seven French warships

438
00:30:48,239 --> 00:30:49,832
to attack Tamsui.

439
00:30:56,815 --> 00:30:58,214
Some 600 French marines

440
00:30:58,450 --> 00:31:00,919
landed on the northeastern coast
of Shalun

441
00:31:01,152 --> 00:31:03,052
to defuse the mines.

442
00:31:06,858 --> 00:31:09,054
In his letter, Orderly Jean,

443
00:31:09,294 --> 00:31:12,320
who was part of this
Tamsui landing,

444
00:31:12,564 --> 00:31:15,124
recounted his experience:

445
00:31:16,568 --> 00:31:18,662
We've landed for the moment.

446
00:31:18,903 --> 00:31:20,428
It was a sand dune.

447
00:31:20,672 --> 00:31:24,631
Our boots sunk in the fine
sand every step of the way.

448
00:31:28,113 --> 00:31:31,981
Suddenly, a volley of bullets
were fired at us.

449
00:31:32,150 --> 00:31:35,609
An astounding number of Chinese

450
00:31:35,854 --> 00:31:39,654
appeared from all directions.

451
00:31:39,891 --> 00:31:45,261
The Ching army was led
by a General Sun.

452
00:31:45,497 --> 00:31:47,261
I don't know how many stars he has.

453
00:31:47,499 --> 00:31:50,161
When we bombarded his fort,

454
00:31:50,401 --> 00:31:54,497
he was inside drinking
champagne and having lunch.

455
00:31:55,340 --> 00:31:58,002
While the Ching and
French armies were

456
00:31:58,176 --> 00:31:59,575
entangled in a fierce battle,

457
00:31:59,811 --> 00:32:01,506
90 foreigners

458
00:32:01,746 --> 00:32:03,475
based in elevated locations in

459
00:32:03,715 --> 00:32:05,683
Hungmaocheng in Tamsui
and Pitsaitou

460
00:32:05,984 --> 00:32:08,009
watched the battle across the water.

461
00:32:08,253 --> 00:32:09,584
British tea merchant Dodd

462
00:32:09,821 --> 00:32:11,721
was among this group of onlookers

463
00:32:11,990 --> 00:32:15,483
who were witnesses to this
fierce battle.

464
00:32:15,727 --> 00:32:18,094
All the foreigners believed
that the gallant general,

465
00:32:18,329 --> 00:32:20,991
Suen Kai-hua,
would protect them from the war

466
00:32:21,232 --> 00:32:23,166
regardless of the outcome.

467
00:32:32,010 --> 00:32:35,105
He has been quartered here
since 1874,

468
00:32:35,346 --> 00:32:37,280
following the Mutan Sha Incident,

469
00:32:37,348 --> 00:32:40,147
which triggered the
Japanese invasion of Taiwan.

470
00:32:40,451 --> 00:32:44,217
As a general,
he was widely loved and respected.

471
00:32:45,323 --> 00:32:47,519
Under General Sun's command,

472
00:32:47,759 --> 00:32:50,023
1500 Ching soldiers and
Taiwanese militiamen

473
00:32:50,261 --> 00:32:52,696
lay in four routes to ambush

474
00:32:52,931 --> 00:32:54,057
and repelled the French army.

475
00:32:54,299 --> 00:32:57,132
Sun and his troops have filled
a glorious page in Taiwan's history.

476
00:33:02,040 --> 00:33:04,634
On Oct. 12,
as his church was destroyed,

477
00:33:04,876 --> 00:33:06,708
Dr. Mackay and his family

478
00:33:06,978 --> 00:33:08,946
took refuge in Hong Kong.

479
00:33:10,114 --> 00:33:11,673
Defeated in Tamsui
for the second time,

480
00:33:11,983 --> 00:33:13,075
French realized that their objective

481
00:33:13,318 --> 00:33:16,618
couldn't be achieved through
military action alone.

482
00:33:16,854 --> 00:33:18,652
The French then announced
a blockade of Taiwan,

483
00:33:18,890 --> 00:33:20,654
prohibiting other foreign ships

484
00:33:20,892 --> 00:33:22,860
from entering the seas of Taiwan.

485
00:33:24,862 --> 00:33:27,194
On Oct. 23, 1884, the French

486
00:33:27,432 --> 00:33:30,527
government authorized
its fleet in the Far East

487
00:33:30,768 --> 00:33:32,293
to run a blockade
of Formosa island

488
00:33:32,537 --> 00:33:32,969
I, Admiral Amedee Courbet

489
00:33:33,204 --> 00:33:37,300
of the French fleet,

490
00:33:37,542 --> 00:33:40,773
view the current situation

491
00:33:41,012 --> 00:33:42,844
and announce the following:

492
00:33:43,081 --> 00:33:45,982
Starting Oct. 23, 1884,

493
00:33:46,150 --> 00:33:50,212
from north latitude 21°50”
at Erhluanpi,

494
00:33:50,455 --> 00:33:54,585
east longitude 118°32”,

495
00:33:54,826 --> 00:34:00,356
passing the eastern and
northern coastal areas

496
00:34:00,598 --> 00:34:03,158
to the south of Su-ao,
north latitude 24°30”,

497
00:34:03,401 --> 00:34:07,429
east longitude 119°35”,

498
00:34:07,672 --> 00:34:11,700
the ports and bays of Taiwan

499
00:34:11,943 --> 00:34:16,039
will be blocked by the French navy.

500
00:34:16,281 --> 00:34:21,947
Ships of neutral country
should unload the merchandise

501
00:34:22,186 --> 00:34:24,621
within three days,
and leave the blockade area.

502
00:34:24,856 --> 00:34:29,089
Attempts to violate the blockade
will be dealt with

503
00:34:29,327 --> 00:34:33,958
according to international law
and existing treaties.

504
00:34:35,900 --> 00:34:38,597
So, a state of anarchy
befell northern Taiwan.

505
00:34:38,836 --> 00:34:41,828
Antagonism against foreigners
caused riots and looting.

506
00:34:42,073 --> 00:34:44,440
Churches were burned
and destroyed.

507
00:34:44,976 --> 00:34:47,604
Two months after the blockade,

508
00:34:47,845 --> 00:34:49,210
British tea merchant Dodd

509
00:34:49,447 --> 00:34:51,006
was forced to evacuate along
with other foreigners.

510
00:34:51,249 --> 00:34:53,343
Dodd left his tea company
in Tataocheng,

511
00:34:53,584 --> 00:34:56,383
and sought refuge inside the
British consulate in Tamsui

512
00:34:56,621 --> 00:34:58,487
In his diary, he described

513
00:34:58,723 --> 00:35:01,158
the deserted Tataocheng

514
00:35:01,392 --> 00:35:02,985
and his despair for the loss
incurred

515
00:35:03,227 --> 00:35:07,186
after his tea trade ended.

516
00:35:13,204 --> 00:35:16,265
This was again another day full of doubt,

517
00:35:16,341 --> 00:35:17,900
guessing, and rumors.

518
00:35:18,142 --> 00:35:21,578
Everybody felt more and more
helpless in these depressing times,

519
00:35:21,813 --> 00:35:23,907
more and more dissatisfied.

520
00:35:25,917 --> 00:35:28,215
If people knew
when the blockade would end,

521
00:35:28,453 --> 00:35:31,218
maybe it would help relax the mood.

522
00:35:34,759 --> 00:35:36,227
December 16.

523
00:35:36,461 --> 00:35:40,056
There was only one German battleship
accompanying us in the harbor,

524
00:35:40,298 --> 00:35:42,027
but we were still quite busy.

525
00:35:42,233 --> 00:35:45,965
With great enthusiasm,
we organized a billiard competition,

526
00:35:46,037 --> 00:35:48,836
as well a tennis competition
on the grass.

527
00:35:51,209 --> 00:35:53,041
Ships. Ships.

528
00:36:20,905 --> 00:36:22,634
To force the hand
of the Ching Dynasty,

529
00:36:22,874 --> 00:36:25,206
the French next captured Pescadores.

530
00:36:25,443 --> 00:36:26,911
The Ching and French

531
00:36:27,145 --> 00:36:30,342
finally on June 6, 1885

532
00:36:30,581 --> 00:36:32,481
signed the Treaty of Tientsin.

533
00:36:32,717 --> 00:36:35,084
The Ching Empire relinquished
its vassal state Annan,

534
00:36:35,319 --> 00:36:37,344
and the war finally ended.

535
00:37:01,979 --> 00:37:04,004
On June 11, 1885,

536
00:37:04,248 --> 00:37:06,740
Admiral Amedee Courbet
of the French fleet,

537
00:37:07,018 --> 00:37:08,144
was infected with cholera

538
00:37:08,386 --> 00:37:10,582
and died on the battleship Bayard.

539
00:37:11,155 --> 00:37:12,179
The French withdrew

540
00:37:12,423 --> 00:37:14,983
leaving behind a devastated Chilung.

541
00:37:15,326 --> 00:37:17,090
Dodd's previous efforts

542
00:37:17,328 --> 00:37:19,387
went up in smoke.

543
00:37:33,911 --> 00:37:35,606
The Sino-French War again

544
00:37:35,847 --> 00:37:37,872
made the Ching Empire realize
the importance of Taiwan as a

545
00:37:38,115 --> 00:37:41,517
shield of the mainland's
southeastern coasts.

546
00:37:41,752 --> 00:37:45,154
Taiwan was thus elevated
to the status of a province,

547
00:37:45,389 --> 00:37:49,053
Liu Ming-chuan became
the first governor of Taiwan.

548
00:37:54,532 --> 00:37:57,524
Liu noted that during the
blockade in the

549
00:37:57,768 --> 00:37:59,634
Sino-French War,
the absence of a telegraph system

550
00:37:59,871 --> 00:38:02,897
hampered communications
with the outside world.

551
00:38:14,218 --> 00:38:16,152
In 1887,

552
00:38:16,387 --> 00:38:18,856
the first undersea cable

553
00:38:19,090 --> 00:38:20,888
was laid between Taiwan and
the mainland China.

554
00:38:21,125 --> 00:38:22,217
For the first time, Taiwan

555
00:38:22,460 --> 00:38:25,486
became connected to
the world's telegraph system.

556
00:38:30,735 --> 00:38:34,194
Liu also began construction
of the cross-island railroad.

557
00:38:34,438 --> 00:38:36,406
With Tataocheng as the hub,
the rail system connected

558
00:38:36,641 --> 00:38:40,771
Chilung to the north
and Hsinchu to the south.

559
00:38:46,217 --> 00:38:47,685
In 1895,

560
00:38:47,919 --> 00:38:49,910
American reporter Davidson,

561
00:38:50,154 --> 00:38:52,589
who worked for the
North China Herald,

562
00:38:52,823 --> 00:38:54,552
came to cover Taiwan.

563
00:38:55,426 --> 00:38:57,485
He remembered vividly the events

564
00:38:57,728 --> 00:38:59,628
surrounding the construction
of the railway.

565
00:39:03,668 --> 00:39:07,969
The routes determined by the engineers
were often changed.

566
00:39:08,172 --> 00:39:13,008
The pale was often taken by the soldiers
to use as firewood.

567
00:39:13,244 --> 00:39:15,975
There was an even grater problem though.

568
00:39:16,147 --> 00:39:18,411
Corruption was in vogue.

569
00:39:18,649 --> 00:39:20,549
In order to preserve the graves,

570
00:39:20,785 --> 00:39:24,653
the routes needed to have sudden curving
to avoid them.

571
00:39:32,797 --> 00:39:35,232
Due to poor construction quality,

572
00:39:35,466 --> 00:39:37,992
the rail system was void
of any practical value.

573
00:39:38,202 --> 00:39:39,260
Shortly after its completion,

574
00:39:39,503 --> 00:39:43,337
the railroad was removed
by the Japanese, Taiwan's new rulers.

575
00:39:59,190 --> 00:40:01,022
After the Mutan Incident,

576
00:40:01,258 --> 00:40:04,558
the Ching Empire sent

577
00:40:04,795 --> 00:40:06,490
Shen Pao-chen and
Tsen Yu-ying to Taiwan

578
00:40:06,731 --> 00:40:10,167
to develop the mountains and
appease the aborigines,

579
00:40:11,035 --> 00:40:12,196
and use development of the mountains

580
00:40:12,436 --> 00:40:15,531
to pay for increasing
military expenses.

581
00:40:15,773 --> 00:40:17,537
Because the mountain
development policy

582
00:40:17,775 --> 00:40:18,765
directly affected and intruded on

583
00:40:19,010 --> 00:40:20,978
the lives of the aborigines,

584
00:40:21,145 --> 00:40:24,410
the policy was often met with
strong resistance by the aborigines.

585
00:40:25,016 --> 00:40:26,848
During Liu's administration,

586
00:40:27,084 --> 00:40:28,711
the Ching took into account

587
00:40:29,020 --> 00:40:31,045
the flourishing tea leaf and
camphor industries

588
00:40:31,288 --> 00:40:32,687
to develop the interior mountains

589
00:40:32,923 --> 00:40:36,291
using large-scale military
operations.

590
00:40:36,527 --> 00:40:37,517
The Ching administration used
the development of

591
00:40:37,762 --> 00:40:40,231
mountains to gain control
over the aborigines.

592
00:40:40,598 --> 00:40:42,623
To develop the low-mountain areas

593
00:40:42,867 --> 00:40:43,993
Liu Ming-chuan adopted the

594
00:40:44,201 --> 00:40:47,102
method of joint development
with rich local gentries.

595
00:40:47,338 --> 00:40:48,999
The most prominent included

596
00:40:49,206 --> 00:40:51,072
Lin Wei-yuan of Panchiao,

597
00:40:51,308 --> 00:40:54,334
Tataocheng merchant
Li Chun-sheng,

598
00:40:55,579 --> 00:40:59,015
Miaoli landowner Huang Nan-chiu,

599
00:41:01,619 --> 00:41:04,486
and the rich and powerful
Li Chao-tung from Wufeng.

600
00:41:10,027 --> 00:41:11,825
Among them,
Lin Wei-yuan of Panchiao

601
00:41:12,063 --> 00:41:14,395
was the richest man in Taiwan
at the time.

602
00:41:14,632 --> 00:41:18,227
His businesses included camphor,
shipping, and private banking.

603
00:41:20,137 --> 00:41:22,663
The camphor oil extracted
from trees

604
00:41:22,907 --> 00:41:24,602
was used as raw material
for insect repellants,

605
00:41:24,842 --> 00:41:28,176
perfume, medicine,
and industrial products.

606
00:41:28,412 --> 00:41:29,641
Taiwan's camphor production
at that time

607
00:41:29,880 --> 00:41:31,814
accounted for 80 percent
of the global production.

608
00:41:32,049 --> 00:41:33,039
Camphor manufacturing was

609
00:41:33,284 --> 00:41:36,549
one of the major industries
in Taiwan.

610
00:41:50,401 --> 00:41:53,393
In his diary,
British tea merchant Dodd

611
00:41:53,637 --> 00:41:56,038
recounted how he had followed
Hakka camphor workers

612
00:41:56,273 --> 00:41:59,436
into the mountains
to process camphor.

613
00:42:01,879 --> 00:42:05,406
The Hakka camphor workers
passed their days in horror.

614
00:42:05,649 --> 00:42:09,950
If they were decapitated in a conflict
with aboriginal warriors,

615
00:42:10,187 --> 00:42:13,316
their Han employers would at most
give them a simple burial

616
00:42:13,390 --> 00:42:15,484
and meager compensation.

617
00:42:15,593 --> 00:42:19,496
They wore aboriginal clothing and
smoke pipes like the aboriginals.

618
00:42:19,597 --> 00:42:21,861
The only characteristic that
distinguished them

619
00:42:21,932 --> 00:42:24,424
from the aboriginals was their
long braids.

620
00:42:24,668 --> 00:42:25,999
Compared to camphor workers,

621
00:42:26,237 --> 00:42:28,535
the aborigines were the major
victims

622
00:42:28,773 --> 00:42:30,172
of the development process.

623
00:42:30,407 --> 00:42:33,570
Liu on three occasions led the
military to suppress

624
00:42:33,811 --> 00:42:36,610
the aborigines to facilitate
mountain development.

625
00:42:36,847 --> 00:42:38,246
Rich merchants of
emerging industries

626
00:42:38,482 --> 00:42:41,383
also joined the suppression
of the aborigines.

627
00:42:42,086 --> 00:42:43,485
American reporter Davidson

628
00:42:43,721 --> 00:42:45,519
lived in Taiwan for eight years.

629
00:42:45,756 --> 00:42:49,056
The issue of camphor was also
that of the raw barbarians.

630
00:42:49,293 --> 00:42:50,419
In his book,

631
00:42:50,661 --> 00:42:52,993
Davidson carefully analyzed
the problem.

632
00:42:54,765 --> 00:42:57,700
To calculate the amount
of camphor balls

633
00:42:57,768 --> 00:43:00,294
the dames used to protect the coats

634
00:43:00,538 --> 00:43:04,202
was the result of
how much blood of the people,

635
00:43:04,441 --> 00:43:08,742
or the camphor that could be used
for curing rheumatism of the elderly,

636
00:43:08,979 --> 00:43:13,041
is obtained by sacrificing
how many human lives.

637
00:43:13,717 --> 00:43:16,982
It was a really a tractive question.

638
00:43:17,555 --> 00:43:21,150
The camphor tress could only grow
in deep forests

639
00:43:21,358 --> 00:43:23,622
where the wild indigenous men lived,

640
00:43:23,861 --> 00:43:27,491
also the home of Taiwan's hunters.

641
00:43:33,737 --> 00:43:38,299
The crimes happen by taking advantage
of all opportunities.

642
00:43:38,542 --> 00:43:41,637
But it was a pity that the violence
did not come

643
00:43:41,712 --> 00:43:43,976
only from the wild indigenous men,

644
00:43:44,181 --> 00:43:45,842
but also the Han people,

645
00:43:46,083 --> 00:43:51,180
who took any chance to avenge
on the wretched indigenous people.

646
00:43:59,697 --> 00:44:02,098
Aborigines were driven out
of the camphor forests,

647
00:44:02,333 --> 00:44:05,132
and young aborigine children
were sent to schools for them.

648
00:44:05,369 --> 00:44:08,964
The government paid food and
clothing to them monthly.

649
00:44:09,607 --> 00:44:11,769
The Ching Empire joined hands
with wealthy merchants

650
00:44:12,009 --> 00:44:14,307
to develop the camphor
industry while exterminating

651
00:44:14,545 --> 00:44:16,604
and pacifying the aborigines
and cultivating the land.

652
00:44:16,847 --> 00:44:17,871
The real beneficiaries
were the wealthy merchants

653
00:44:18,115 --> 00:44:20,914
who collaborated with the
government.

654
00:44:21,151 --> 00:44:23,085
During this development process,

655
00:44:23,320 --> 00:44:24,116
stories of the aborigines

656
00:44:24,355 --> 00:44:26,790
protecting their ancestral homes

657
00:44:27,024 --> 00:44:28,651
and sacrificing their lives

658
00:44:28,893 --> 00:44:30,861
were ignored and forgotten.

659
00:44:33,464 --> 00:44:36,229
From the Opium War,
Mutan Incident,

660
00:44:36,467 --> 00:44:37,992
to the Sino-French War,

661
00:44:38,235 --> 00:44:39,930
late 19th century Taiwan

662
00:44:40,170 --> 00:44:43,299
had been prey for the

663
00:44:43,540 --> 00:44:45,599
Eastern and Western
imperial powers.

664
00:44:47,211 --> 00:44:49,612
To the descendants of the
Han Chinese,

665
00:44:49,847 --> 00:44:51,713
this had been a bitter and arduous

666
00:44:51,949 --> 00:44:53,815
saga of their ancestors.

667
00:44:54,084 --> 00:44:56,644
Yet to the original residents
of the island,

668
00:44:56,887 --> 00:44:58,377
the aborigines,

669
00:44:58,622 --> 00:45:01,319
it was the beginning of a glum future.

670
00:45:05,829 --> 00:45:08,821
They were driven out
of their ancestral homes

671
00:45:09,066 --> 00:45:11,694
and gradually lost their
traditional culture.

672
00:45:12,036 --> 00:45:15,097
As the administration on the
island changed hands,

673
00:45:15,339 --> 00:45:19,003
more drastic and dramatic
changes would befall them.

